  <div class="article_date">Last Updated: {article.lastUpdatedOnDate}</div>
  <span class="article_readminutes"><auro-icon category="interface" name="calendar" ariaHidden="false"></auro-icon> {article.minutes} min. read</span>
  <span class="article_tags"><auro-icon category="interface" name="tag" ariaHidden="false"></auro-icon> <auro-hyperlink href="https://auro-examples.vercel.app/newsletter">Bunnies</auro-hyperlink>, <auro-hyperlink href="https://auro-examples.vercel.app/newsletter">Badgers</auro-hyperlink>, <auro-hyperlink href="https://auro-examples.vercel.app/newsletter">Beavers</auro-hyperlink></span>
  <div class="article_summary">TLDR; In the air travel industry where stakes fly high, Alaska Airlines leverages Figma’s advanced design system features to build a cohesive digital experience and ship new products faster.</div>
  <div class="article_full"><div class="css-gri2f1"><div><div colorscheme="[object Object]"><p class="css-1l0ig77">As an early adopter of technology, Alaska Airlines is no stranger to innovation: It’s pioneered check-in kiosks, electronic bag tags, and mobile boarding passes within the travel industry. It was even the <a href="https://news.alaskaair.com/alaska-airlines/alaska-first-to-sell-tickets-internet/#:~:text=This%20news%20release%20was%20originally,host%2Dto%2Dhost%20connection." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" class="css-1qsits3">first airline to sell tickets online</a> in 1995. For Alaska, progress is table stakes when it comes to expanding its geographic footprint and providing the best customer experience—as demonstrated by its top ranking in the <a href="https://www.theacsi.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/23apr_TRAVEL-Report.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" class="css-1qsits3">2023 American Customer Satisfaction Index travel&nbsp;list</a>.</p><p class="css-1l0ig77">Today, as Alaska’s digital design team of roughly 45 people manages a growing number of interfaces, it's become more challenging and complex to ensure a consistent user experience.They’re no longer just ensuring a seamless UX across a single website, but across each of these new touchpoints, which include mobile, digital signage, and kiosks. Figma has enabled Alaska to build a design system that can achieve greater consistency and serve as the catalyst for high-impact, high-value company projects. Since implementing variables in Figma, designers at Alaska Air are saving an average of 11 hours of work&nbsp;per&nbsp;week.</p><div class="css-y13vud"><figure class="css-eunxs4"><div><div class="mediaAnimationWrapper css-vpo6wu" style="clip-path: inset(0%);"><img class="css-10klw3m" width="804" height="534" loading="lazy" alt="An image shows examples of Alaska’s design system, including a color palette of light to dark blue hues, alert badges, buttons, and icons " src="https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/d17ed82f122d2d258b8308b65b810ea7f252071d-1198x795.png?rect=1,0,1197,795&amp;w=804&amp;h=534&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format" srcset="https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/d17ed82f122d2d258b8308b65b810ea7f252071d-1198x795.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=0.5 402w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/d17ed82f122d2d258b8308b65b810ea7f252071d-1198x795.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=0.75 603w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/d17ed82f122d2d258b8308b65b810ea7f252071d-1198x795.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format 804w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/d17ed82f122d2d258b8308b65b810ea7f252071d-1198x795.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=2 1197w"></div></div><figcaption class="css-6vor94">Foundation of Alaska’s design components</figcaption></figure></div><p class="css-1l0ig77">Take the company’s flight status page for example. When severe weather storms hit a few years ago, the onslaught of flight disruptions revealed limitations in the pre-existing flight status page, which was underutilized and lacking critical information for passengers like a flight tracker map and aircraft details. Eager to improve the customer experience, a tiger team of designers and engineers came together to redesign this page. By pulling 90% of components from the Auro design system in Figma, the team was able to achieve this initiative with limited resources and in record time. From start to finish, the new page came together in a single sprint—without Figma, it would have taken at least four or five sprints to complete. Today the flight status page is one of the most utilized pages on the app today, with “average time on page” increasing from 36 seconds to five minutes and&nbsp;10&nbsp;seconds.</p><div class="css-y13vud"><figure class="css-eunxs4"><div><div class="mediaAnimationWrapper css-vpo6wu" style="clip-path: inset(0%);"><img class="css-10klw3m" width="804" height="347" loading="lazy" alt="Two screens show how the updated flight status page includes more information like a flight status tracker" src="https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/405fd03a7dfd63d4575aac154a784f4671252fa5-3229x1395.png?rect=0,1,3229,1394&amp;w=804&amp;h=347&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format" srcset="https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/405fd03a7dfd63d4575aac154a784f4671252fa5-3229x1395.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=0.5 402w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/405fd03a7dfd63d4575aac154a784f4671252fa5-3229x1395.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=0.75 603w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/405fd03a7dfd63d4575aac154a784f4671252fa5-3229x1395.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format 804w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/405fd03a7dfd63d4575aac154a784f4671252fa5-3229x1395.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=1.5 1206w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/405fd03a7dfd63d4575aac154a784f4671252fa5-3229x1395.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=2 1608w"></div></div><figcaption class="css-6vor94">Before and after of Alaska’s flight status page</figcaption></figure></div><h2 id="addressing-an-inconsistent-ux" class="css-vsobh0"><a href="#addressing-an-inconsistent-ux" class="css-1bs7qd7">Addressing an inconsistent UX</a></h2><p class="css-1l0ig77">With their previous tech stack consisting of Sketch and Invision, Alaska’s design system was a “bit of a Frankenstein system,” says Dale Sande, Principal Engineer at Alaska. The library enabled engineers to meet correct design specs, but it fell short for designers, who couldn’t quickly pull components for their&nbsp;designs.</p><p class="css-1l0ig77">Without a source of truth they could reference, designers found themselves creating components and patterns that were several pixels off—in some cases, designers adjusted the colors through a slider in the browser. These manual approaches not only took longer, but led to inconsistent experiences across buttons, checkboxes, modals, colors, and date pickers, with varying accessibility standards. Internally, collaboration between designers and engineers suffered, as engineers became increasingly frustrated upon receiving designs that didn’t match the&nbsp;website.</p><p class="css-1l0ig77">June Lee, Product Designer at Alaska, details a few of their challenges: “Sketch and Invision lacked intuitive user experiences, tools for prototyping, and real-time team work. Unlike Figma components, their concept of reusable widgets didn’t provide an elegant solution. Plus the lack of a shared design library meant that any changes had to be manually copy and pasted.” While Abstract enabled them to collaborate on Sketch files, they struggled with the versioning. Since moving to Figma, Alaska has been able to establish a design system that provides the right documentation for both designers and engineers—a critical step to building a consistent digital ecosystem and innovating faster on the most impactful projects.</p><h2 id="designer-and-engineering-collaboration-takes-off" class="css-vsobh0"><a href="#designer-and-engineering-collaboration-takes-off" class="css-1bs7qd7">Designer and engineering collaboration takes off with&nbsp;Figma</a></h2><p class="css-1l0ig77">As June shares, “When we migrated from Sketch to Figma, the initial selling point was that Figma could be the tool for designers to collaborate together. As we started utilizing more and more of Figma’s design system features, we realized that we could bring engineering in as well and help them understand the design ideas behind Auro, Alaska’s design&nbsp;system.”</p><div class="css-y13vud"><figure class="css-eunxs4"><div><div class="mediaAnimationWrapper css-vpo6wu" style="clip-path: inset(0%);"><img class="css-10klw3m" width="804" height="531" loading="lazy" alt="A collage of pages showcases different aspects of Alaska’s design system, like colors and menu types" src="https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/0d1df2ffccb145b181ad0aab2ed4554ca8654d0f-1324x874.png?rect=1,0,1323,874&amp;w=804&amp;h=531&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format" srcset="https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/0d1df2ffccb145b181ad0aab2ed4554ca8654d0f-1324x874.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=0.5 402w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/0d1df2ffccb145b181ad0aab2ed4554ca8654d0f-1324x874.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=0.75 603w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/0d1df2ffccb145b181ad0aab2ed4554ca8654d0f-1324x874.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format 804w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/0d1df2ffccb145b181ad0aab2ed4554ca8654d0f-1324x874.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=1.5 1206w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/0d1df2ffccb145b181ad0aab2ed4554ca8654d0f-1324x874.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=2 1323w"></div></div><figcaption class="css-6vor94">Snapshot of Alaska’s design patterns</figcaption></figure></div><p class="css-1l0ig77">Figma’s design system features have marked a new chapter for design and engineering teams at Alaska. Designers can now reference the components that mirror the web components used by engineers. This 1:1 match facilitated greater consistency in their products, and in turn, reduced confusion among engineers. Brandon Shields, Product Manager at Alaska, adds, “Beyond streamlining our processes, engineers can be more confident that certain designs can be implemented easily.”</p><p class="css-1l0ig77">As June established the Auro design system in Figma, she also built out documentation on how to use features like auto-layout and merging and branching to better educate the designers and increase adoption. June says, “I really focused on education with our designers so they could understand what Figma could do. I could see that designers were better utilizing Figma, and that meant that conflicts previously happening between designers and engineers were decreasing.”</p><h2 id="with-variables-auro-design-system-reaches-new" class="css-vsobh0"><a href="#with-variables-auro-design-system-reaches-new" class="css-1bs7qd7">With variables, Auro design system reaches new&nbsp;heights</a></h2><p class="css-1l0ig77">For a company of over 23,000 full-time employees, it’s critical that the design team can scale their work to serve more teams and create greater impact. The introduction of variables within Figma has made this&nbsp;possible.</p><p class="css-1l0ig77">In their everyday workflows, the Alaska design team uses variables to design for various screen sizes faster, design for light and dark mode, and enable theming for internal teams and external partners. Variables have allowed the design team to support internal sub-teams without a big lift, ultimately freeing them up to work on more impactful projects.</p><div class="css-y13vud"><figure class="css-eunxs4"><div><div class="mediaAnimationWrapper css-vpo6wu" style="clip-path: inset(0%);"><img class="css-10klw3m" width="804" height="515" loading="lazy" alt="Two overlapping screens show color variables set up within Figma" src="https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/5c17a3c789e5ddcbb42dd59192b7ddf958f0cea6-2496x1600.png?rect=0,1,2496,1599&amp;w=804&amp;h=515&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format" srcset="https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/5c17a3c789e5ddcbb42dd59192b7ddf958f0cea6-2496x1600.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=0.5 402w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/5c17a3c789e5ddcbb42dd59192b7ddf958f0cea6-2496x1600.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=0.75 603w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/5c17a3c789e5ddcbb42dd59192b7ddf958f0cea6-2496x1600.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format 804w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/5c17a3c789e5ddcbb42dd59192b7ddf958f0cea6-2496x1600.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=1.5 1206w, https://cdn.sanity.io/images/599r6htc/localized/5c17a3c789e5ddcbb42dd59192b7ddf958f0cea6-2496x1600.png?w=804&amp;q=75&amp;fit=max&amp;auto=format&amp;dpr=2 1608w"></div></div><figcaption class="css-6vor94">Alaska’s variables set up in Figma</figcaption></figure></div><p class="css-1l0ig77">Before <a class="css-1qsits3" href="/blog/config-2023-recap/#with-variables-design-systems-speak-the-same">variables were launched at Config</a> in 2023, designers had to recall the raw values for things like border radius, padding, and color. To make it easier for designers and improve handoffs, June, as an internal Figma champion, would manually type out the design token name in the description of the color style. Variables have made this workflow obsolete, and in her words, is a “huge, huge step in bringing designers closer to the design system thinking and code.” With variables, both internal and external facing products can leverage Auro’s components with a customized theme. And, they’re creating primitive, semantic, and component-specific design tokens with variables to create new modes for each branded&nbsp;theme.</p><div class="breakout-block css-i9yes9"><button class="css-1mlot65"><div aria-live="polite" class="css-1l3f14b">Copied<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 28 28" class="css-o23duq"><path fill="#699BF7" stroke="#000" d="M23.1 19.25a10.5 10.5 0 0 1-13.9 4.07v.02l-.44-.26a10.5 10.5 0 0 1-4.07-13.9h-.01l.25-.43a10.5 10.5 0 0 1 18.17 10.5Z"></path><circle cx="1.06" cy="1.06" r="1.06" fill="#000" transform="rotate(30.03 -9.65 26) skewX(-.01)"></circle><circle cx="1.06" cy="1.06" r="1.06" fill="#000" transform="rotate(30.03 -13.42 40.04) skewX(-.01)"></circle><path stroke="#000" d="M20.04 17.49A6.96 6.96 0 0 1 8 10.52"></path></svg></div><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 14 12" class="css-ykdrjc"><path fill="#fff" fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.752 1.189c.694 0 1.327.277 1.822.752L7.98 3.347l.832-.831L7.406 1.11A3.749 3.749 0 0 0 4.752 0C3.742 0 2.812.398 2.1 1.11A3.749 3.749 0 0 0 .99 3.763c0 .99.396 1.94 1.109 2.654l1.406 1.406.832-.832L2.93 5.585a2.53 2.53 0 0 1-.753-1.822c0-.693.277-1.327.753-1.822.475-.495 1.128-.752 1.821-.752Zm5.743 2.988-.832.832 1.406 1.406a2.53 2.53 0 0 1 .753 1.822 2.61 2.61 0 0 1-.753 1.822 2.529 2.529 0 0 1-1.821.752 2.612 2.612 0 0 1-1.822-.752L6.02 8.653l-.832.831 1.406 1.406A3.749 3.749 0 0 0 9.248 12c1.01 0 1.94-.397 2.653-1.11a3.749 3.749 0 0 0 1.109-2.653c0-.99-.396-1.94-1.109-2.654l-1.406-1.406ZM5.73 3.901l-.84.84L8.25 8.1l.84-.84L5.73 3.9Z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg></button><figure class="css-1uk1gs8"><blockquote class="css-1vzsn0k"><span class="css-1x5wvak">Since implementing variables in Figma, designers at Alaska Air are saving an average of 11 hours of work per week.</span><div aria-hidden="true"><span class="css-1mr4x4q" style="opacity: 1;">“<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">Since<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">implementing<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">variables<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">in<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">Figma,<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">designers<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">at<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">Alaska<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">Air<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">are<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">saving<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">an<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">average<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">of<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">11<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">hours<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">of<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">work<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">per<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">week.<!-- --> </span><span class="css-0" style="opacity: 1;">”</span></div></blockquote></figure></div><p class="css-1l0ig77">The ability to change an entire design simply by setting up various modes is a game changer for Alaska’s design team. Dale speaks to the value of no-code: “We can really help designers understand the flexibility of what we can do with CSS variables and design tokens. By simply replacing a set of variables with a different set of values, we can drastically change the whole environment without actually having to edit any code. Previously these changes were walled off by the coding&nbsp;world.”</p><div class="css-y13vud"><figure class="css-eunxs4"><div><div class="mediaAnimationWrapper css-vpo6wu" style="clip-path: inset(0%);"><div class="css-1oiwlqa"><video src="https://cdn.sanity.io/files/599r6htc/localized/7ce5a2ae99324212ee7834f21f4c498fba2d29bc.mp4" autoplay="" playsinline="" muted="" loop="" width="100%" height="auto" class="css-1ywmljq"></video><button class="blog-play-pause-button css-anxbvf" aria-label="pause"><svg width="19" height="19" viewBox="0 0 25 25" fill="none" style="display:inline-block;vertical-align:middle"><rect x="4.78748" y="1.72461" width="6.12498" height="21.6212" fill="currentColor"></rect><rect x="14.5875" y="1.72461" width="6.12498" height="21.6212" fill="currentColor"></rect></svg></button></div></div></div><figcaption class="css-6vor94">With variables, Alaska can easily switch between light and dark mode.</figcaption></figure></div><p class="css-1l0ig77">Forever forward-thinking, the team plans to continue leveraging Figma in deeper and more powerful ways. As Dale says, “There’s a huge design effort underway which is going to increase the number of design tokens, opening the floodgates for customization and theming. We’re really looking to take advantage of what Figma is giving us today to power that process going into the&nbsp;future.”</p><p class="css-1l0ig77"><strong>True to their roots, Alaska Airlines is constantly moving the needle on innovation. With the sky as the limit, Figma’s design system features enable Alaska to achieve a more consistent digital experience, better collaboration between designers and developers, and greater efficiencies for their design&nbsp;team.</strong></p></div></div></div></div>
</article>

